  "notes": "This is a field study using difference-in-differences estimation with propensity score matching. The paper leverages ChatGPT's November 2022 release as a quasi-natural experiment. The main finding is that AI-written practice descriptions increase patient demand on average (1.6 percentage point increase in waitlist probability, a 25% relative increase), but inexperienced practice owners experience reduced demand due to aggressive price increases following adoption. The paper includes a custom BERT-based classifier trained to detect ChatGPT-written descriptions. The heterogeneous treatment effect is explained by a behavioral mechanism where inexperienced owners overestimate the quality of AI-generated content, leading to non-profit-maximizing price increases. The author notes several caveats: (1) the choice of prompt constitutes an implicit assumption about how practices use ChatGPT; (2) the detector may not catch every instance of ChatGPT adoption; (3) the paper does not observe whether practices use ChatGPT for other business purposes; (4) the paper does not observe actual patient numbers, only a coarse measure of demand (waitlist indicator); (5) demand effects are attenuated if practices are not close to capacity; (6) practices could use ChatGPT for other marketing or business processes beyond description rewriting. The author also notes that ChatGPT during the study period was not compliant with health data security standards. After applying Bonferroni correction, there is one significant differential effect for inexperienced therapists out of 117 variables tested (a slightly positive value for \"curiosity\" associated words).",
  "_paper_id": "Can_AI_Improve_Marketing_Communications_for_Small_Businesses_Field_Evidence_fro"
}